# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: elmer-ambrose-sperry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] The **Aero Club of America** was a social club formed in 1905 by Charles Jasper Glidden and Augustus Post, among others, to promote aviation in the United States.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] It was the parent organization of numerous state chapters, the first being the Aero Club of New England.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] It thrived until 1923, when it transformed into the National Aeronautic Association, which still exists today.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] It issued the first pilot's licenses in the United States, and successful completion of its licensing process was required by the United States Army for its pilots until 1914.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] It sponsored numerous air shows and contests.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Cortlandt Field Bishop was president in 1910.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Starting in 1911, new president Robert J.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Collier began presenting the Collier Trophy.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Although conventional wisdom states that the Aero Club began in 1905, there are photos of high society and adventurers printed in 1902 with the stamp, "Aero Club".
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] In the summer of 1905 several members of the Automobile Club of America including Charles Glidden, Homer Hedge, Dave Morris, John F.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] O'Rourke, and Augustus Post founded the Aero Club of America.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] They were avid balloonists but found little support in America for the *sport* of aviation.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] They determined to establish a new club with an organization similar to the Automobile Club but whose purpose was to promote aviation, much like the Aero Club of France.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Homer Hedge became the first President and Augustus Post the first secretary.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] In 1910, three different conventions were held in New York among aeronautical clubs and societies.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] The National Council of Affiliated Clubs of the Aero Club of America, was formed.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Thirty-nine delegates, representing constituencies from Pasadena, California, to Boston, met at the Aero Club and formed the parent organization of various state chapters.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] At the International Aviation Meet at Belmont Park in October 1910, a considerable controversy arose between the Englishman Claude Graham-White and the American J.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] In one race around the Statue of Liberty, Graham-White won by several minutes, but due to a technicality, the race and considerable prize money was awarded to Moisant.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] John Armstrong Drexel made public statements accusing the organization of favoritism toward its own members, and Drexel held a competing dinner banquet at the same time as the awards banquet of the organization.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] The schism among the membership threatened the integrity of the organization, but was ultimately resolved with Drexel's resignation.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] In 1911, the Aero Club of New York put on the First Industrial Airplane Show that was held in conjunction with the 11th U.S.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] International Auto Show at Manhattan's Grand Central Palace, in New York City.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] It was a spectacular event with prominent speakers, and an enthusiastic large crowd that would gaze upon a full-size airplane for the first time.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] It started December 31, 1910, until mid-January 1911.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] In 1919, the secretary of the club, Augustus Post organized and drew up the rules for a transatlantic flight competition between New York and Paris.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] He worked with wealthy hotel owner Raymond Orteig in securing the $25,000 for the Orteig Prize.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] The $25,000 prize was to be awarded "to the first aviator of any Allied Country crossing the Atlantic in one flight, from Paris to New York or New York to Paris".
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] After five years of failing to attract competitors, the award was then put under the control of a seven-member Bryant Bank board of trustees, which awarded it to Charles Lindbergh for his successful 1927 flight in the *Spirit of St.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Some of the later licenses issued by the Aero Club of America bore the printed signature of Orville Wright.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Wright served for a time as Chairman of the Aero Club of America's Contest Committee.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Contrary to popular myth, the Wright brothers were not issued licenses number 4 and 5 for malicious reasons.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] They were simply among the five pilots who had, in America, demonstrated their ability to fly airplanes before the Aero Club of America's licensing program began.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Those first five licenses were issued in alphabetical order — a practice followed by other national organizations belonging to the FAI.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Pilot's licenses were not required by law (except by some states) until well after World War I.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] The National Aeroplane Fund was sanctioned by the Aero Club of America in response to perceived military and political disinterest in aeronautics.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Established in summer 1915, the group lobbied Congress to increase funding for military aeronautics.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] The purpose of The American National Aeroplane Fund was to train aviators, provide aviation corps for the National Guard and Navy Militia of the States and U.S.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Possessions, and put aeroplanes in use for the mail carrying service to inaccessible places, forming an aeronautical reserve, which while being used daily for peaceful purposes shall be ready for military service in case of need.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Some notable early pilots issued licenses by the Aero Club of America are listed below.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-america] Note: "Dirigible" simply meant that the airship could be made to go in any direction.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-france] The **Aéro-Club de France** (French: [a.e.ʁɔ.klyb də fʁɑ̃s]) is one of the oldest French aviators' associations still active.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-france] It was founded as the **Aéro-Club** on 20 October 1898 as a society 'to encourage aerial locomotion' by Ernest Archdeacon, Léon Serpollet, Henri de la Valette, Jules Verne and his wife, André Michelin, Albert de Dion, Alberto Santos-Dumont, Henri Deutsch de la Meurthe, and Henry de La Vaulx.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-france] On 20 April 1909, its name was changed to *Aéro-Club de France*.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-france] The Aéro-Club de France originally set many of the regulations that controlled aviation in France.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-france] The club published the journal *L'Aérophile* from 1898 to 1947, and since 1997 publishes the magazine *Aérofrance*.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-france] The Aéro-Club de France was a founding member of the International Aeronautical Federation (FAI) in 1905, a joint effort with other national associations.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-france] After 1945, some of the Aéro-Club's regulatory roles were taken by other bodies.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-france] It now focusses on the promotion of aviation and certification.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aero-club-of-france] The Club grants the Great Medal of the Aéro-Club de France to individuals who have made outstanding contributions to the advancement of aviation.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] An **aileron** (French for 'little wing' or 'fin') is a hinged flight control surface usually forming part of the trailing edge of each wing of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Ailerons are used in pairs to control the aircraft in roll (or movement around the aircraft's longitudinal axis), which normally results in a change in flight path due to the tilting of the lift vector.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Movement around this axis is called rolling or banking.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Considerable controversy exists over credit for the invention of the aileron.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The Wright brothers and Glenn Curtiss fought a years-long legal battle over the Wright patent of 1906, which described a method of wing-warping to achieve lateral control.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The brothers prevailed in several court decisions which found that Curtiss's use of ailerons violated the Wright patent.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Ultimately, the First World War compelled the U.S.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Government to legislate a legal resolution.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] A much earlier aileron concept was patented in 1868 by British scientist Matthew Piers Watt Boulton, based on his 1864 paper *On Aërial Locomotion*.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The name "aileron", from French, meaning "little wing", also refers to the extremities of a bird's wings used to control their flight.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] It first appeared in print in the 7th edition of Cassell's French-English Dictionary of 1877, with its lead meaning of "small wing".
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] In the context of powered airplanes it appears in print about 1908.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Prior to that, ailerons were often referred to as rudders, their older technical sibling, with no distinction between their orientations and functions, or more descriptively as *horizontal rudders* (in French, *gouvernails horizontaux*).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Among the earliest printed aeronautical use of 'aileron' was that in the French aviation journal *L'Aérophile* of 1908.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Ailerons had more or less completely supplanted other forms of lateral control, such as wing warping, by about 1915, well after the function of the rudder and elevator flight controls had been largely standardised.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] He was the first to patent an aileron control system in 1868.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Boulton's description of his lateral flight control system was "the first record we have of appreciation of the necessity for active lateral control as distinguished from [passive lateral stability]....
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] With this invention of Boulton's we have the birth of the present-day three torque method of airborne control" as was praised by Charles Manly.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] 392 of 1868, issued about 35 years before ailerons were "reinvented" in France, became forgotten and lost from sight until after the flight control device was in general use.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Gibbs-Smith stated on several occasions that if the Boulton patent had been revealed at the time of the Wright brothers' legal filings, they might not have been able to claim priority of invention for the lateral control of flying machines.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The fact that the Wright brothers were able to gain a patent in 1906 did not invalidate Boulton's lost and forgotten invention.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The pioneering U.S. aeronautical engineer Octave Chanute published descriptions and drawings of the Wright brothers' 1902 glider in the leading aviation periodical of the day, *L'Aérophile*, in 1903.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] This prompted Esnault-Pelterie, a French military engineer, to build a Wright-style glider in 1904 that used ailerons in lieu of wing warping.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The French journal *L'Aérophile* then published photos of the ailerons on Esnault-Pelterie's glider which were included in his June 1905 article, and its ailerons were widely copied afterward.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The Wright brothers used wing warping instead of ailerons for roll control on their glider in 1902, and about 1904 their Flyer II was the only aircraft of its time able to do a coordinated banked turn.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] During the early years of powered flight the Wrights had better roll control on their designs than airplanes that used movable surfaces.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] From 1908, as aileron designs were refined it became clear that ailerons were much more effective and practical than wing warping.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Ailerons also had the advantage of not weakening the airplane's wing structure as did the wing warping technique, which was one reason for Esnault-Pelterie's decision to switch to ailerons.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] By 1911, most biplanes used ailerons rather than wing warping—by 1915, ailerons had become almost universal on monoplanes as well.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Government, frustrated by the lack of its country's aeronautical advances in the years leading up to World War I, enforced a patent pool effectively putting an end to the Wright brothers patent war.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The Wright company quietly changed its aircraft flight controls from wing warping to the use of ailerons at that time as well.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The Wright Brothers' Ohio patent attorney Henry Toulmin filed an expansive patent application and on May 22, 1906, the brothers were granted U.S.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The patent's importance lay in its claim of a new and useful method of *controlling* an airplane.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The patent application included the claim for the lateral control of aircraft flight that was not limited to wing warping, but through any manipulation of the "....angular relations of the lateral margins of the airplanes [wings].... varied in opposite directions".
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Thus the patent explicitly stated that other methods besides wing-warping could be used for adjusting the outer portions of an airplane's wings to different angles on its right and left sides to achieve lateral roll control.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Patent 831173 at nearly the same time for his methods of wing warping.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Both the Wright Brothers patent and Montgomery's patent were reviewed and approved by the same patent examiner at the United States Patent Office, William Townsend.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] At the time Townsend indicated that both methods of wing warping were invented independently and were sufficiently different to each justify their own patent award.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Multiple U.S. court decisions favoured the expansive Wright patent, which the Wright Brothers sought to enforce with licensing fees starting from $1,000 per airplane, and said to range up to $1,000 per day.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Casey, a former curator of the Smithsonian Air & Space Museum in Washington, D.C., and other researchers, due to the patent they had received the Wrights stood firmly on the position that all flying using lateral roll control, anywhere in the world, would only be conducted under license by them.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Years of protracted legal conflict ensued with many other aircraft builders until the U.S. entered World War I, when the government imposed a legislated agreement among the parties which resulted in royalty payments of 1% to the Wrights.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] There are still conflicting claims today over who first invented the aileron.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Other 19th century engineers and scientists, including Charles Renard, Alphonse Pénaud, and Louis Mouillard, had described similar flight control surfaces.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Another technique for lateral flight control, wing warping, was also described or experimented with by several people including Jean-Marie Le Bris, John Montgomery, Clement Ader, Edson Gallaudet, D.D.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Gibbs-Smith wrote that the aileron was "....one of the most remarkable inventions... of aeronautical history, which was immediately lost sight of".
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Ailerons are usually situated near the wing tip, but may sometimes also be situated nearer the wing root.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Modern airliners may also have a second pair of ailerons on their wings, with the two positions distinguished by the terms "outboard aileron" and "inboard aileron".
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] An unwanted side effect of aileron operation is adverse yaw, a yawing moment in the opposite direction to the roll.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Using the ailerons to roll an aircraft to the right produces a yawing motion to the left.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] As the aircraft rolls, adverse yaw is caused partly by the change in drag between the left and right wing.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The rising wing generates increased lift, which causes increased induced drag.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The descending wing generates reduced lift, which causes reduced induced drag.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Profile drag caused by the deflected ailerons may add further to the difference, along with changes in the lift vectors as one rotates back while the other rotates forward.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] In a coordinated turn, adverse yaw is effectively compensated by the use of the rudder, which results in a sideforce on the vertical tail that opposes the adverse yaw by creating a favorable yawing moment.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Another method of compensation is "differential ailerons", which have been rigged so that the down-going aileron deflects less than the up-going one.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] In this case the opposing yaw moment is generated by a difference in profile drag between the left and right wingtips.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Ailerons may also be designed to use a combination of these methods.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] With ailerons in the neutral position, the wing on the outside of the turn develops more lift than the opposite wing due to the variation in airspeed across the wing span, which tends to cause the aircraft to continue to roll.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Once the desired angle of bank (degree of rotation about the longitudinal axis) has been obtained, the pilot uses opposite aileron to prevent the angle of bank from increasing due to this variation in lift across the wing span.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] This minor opposite use of the control must be maintained throughout the turn.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The pilot also uses a slight amount of rudder in the same direction as the turn to counteract adverse yaw and to produce a "coordinated" turn wherein the fuselage is parallel to the flight path.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] A simple gauge on the instrument panel called the slip indicator, also known as "the ball", indicates when this coordination is achieved.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Particularly on larger or faster aircraft, control forces may be extremely heavy.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Borrowing a discovery from boats that extending a control surface's area forward of the hinge lightens the forces needed first appeared on ailerons during World War I when ailerons were extended beyond the wingtip and provided with a horn ahead of the hinge.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Known as overhung ailerons, possibly the best known examples are the Handley Page Type O (first flight 17 December 1915), Sopwith Snipe, Fokker Dr.I and Fokker D.VII.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Later examples brought the counterbalance in line with the wing to improve control and reduce drag.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] This is seen less often now, due to the Frise type aileron which provides the same benefit.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Trim tabs are small movable sections resembling scaled down ailerons located at or near the trailing edge of the aileron.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] On most propeller powered aircraft, the rotation of the propellers induces a counteracting roll movement due to Newton's third law of motion, in that every action has an equal and opposite reaction.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] To relieve the pilot of having to provide continuous pressure on the stick in one direction, which causes fatigue, trim tabs are provided to adjust or *trim out* the pressure needed against any unwanted movement.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The tab itself is deflected in relation to the aileron, causing the aileron to move in the opposite direction.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Trim tabs come in two forms, adjustable and fixed.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] A fixed trim tab is manually bent to the required amount of deflection, while the adjustable trim tab can be controlled from within the cockpit so that different power settings or flight attitudes can be compensated for.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Some large aircraft from the 1950s (including the Canadair Argus) used free floating control surfaces that the pilot controlled only through the deflection of trim tabs, in which case additional tabs were also provided to fine-tune the control to provide straight and level flight.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Spades are flat metal plates, usually attached to the aileron lower surface, ahead of the aileron hinge, by a lever arm.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] They reduce the force needed by the pilot to deflect the aileron and are often seen on aerobatic aircraft.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] As the aileron is deflected upward, the spade produces a downward aerodynamic force, which tends to rotate the whole assembly so as to further deflect the aileron upward.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The size of the spade (and its lever arm) determines how much force the pilot needs to apply to deflect the aileron.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] A spade works in the same manner as a horn but is more effective due to the longer moment arm.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] To increase the speed at which control surface flutter (aeroelastic flutter) might become a risk, the center of gravity of the control surface is moved towards the hinge-line for that surface.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] To achieve this, lead weights may be added to the front of the aileron.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] In some aircraft the aileron construction may be too heavy to allow this system to work without an excessive increase in the weight of the aileron.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] In this case, the weight may be added to a lever arm to move the weight well out in front to the aileron body.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] These balance weights are tear drop shaped (to reduce drag), which make them appear quite different from spades, although both project forward and below the aileron.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] In addition to reducing the risk of flutter, mass balances also reduce the stick forces required to move the control surface in maneuvers.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Used during aviation's pre-war "pioneer era" and into the early years of the First World War, these ailerons were each controlled by a single cable, which pulled the aileron up.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] When the aircraft was at rest, the ailerons hung vertically down.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] This type of aileron was used on the Farman III biplane 1909 and the Short 166.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] A "reverse" version of this, utilizing wing-warping, existed on the later version of the Santos-Dumont *Demoiselle*, which only warped the wingtips "downward".
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] One of the disadvantages of this setup was a greater tendency to yaw than even with basic interconnected ailerons.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] During the 1930s, a number of light aircraft used single acting controls but used springs to return the ailerons to their neutral positions when the stick was released.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The main problem with this type of aileron is the dangerous tendency to stall if used aggressively, especially if the aircraft is already in danger of stalling, hence the use primarily on prototypes, and their replacement on production aircraft with more conventional ailerons.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Engineer Leslie George Frise (1897–1979) of the Bristol Aeroplane Company developed an aileron shape that is pivoted at about its 25 to 30% chord line and near its bottom surface , in order to decrease stick forces as aircraft became faster during the 1930s.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] When the aileron is deflected up (to make its wing go down), the leading edge of the aileron starts to protrude below the underside of the wing into the airflow beneath the wing.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The moment of the leading edge in the airflow helps to move up the trailing edge, which decreases the stick force.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The down moving aileron also adds energy to the boundary layer.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The edge of the aileron directs air flow from the underside of the wing to the upper surface of the aileron, thus creating a lifting force added to the lift of the wing.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] This reduces the needed deflection of the aileron.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Both the Canadian Fleet Model 2 biplane of 1930 and the 1938 popular US Piper J-3 Cub monoplane possessed Frise ailerons as designed and helped introduce them to a wide audience.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] A claimed benefit of the Frise aileron is the ability to counteract adverse yaw.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] To do so, the leading edge of the aileron has to be sharp or bluntly rounded, which adds significant drag to the upturned aileron and helps counterbalance the yaw force created by the other aileron turned down.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] This can add some unpleasant, nonlinear effect and/or potentially dangerous aerodynamic vibration (flutter).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Adverse yaw moment is basically countered by aircraft yaw stability and also by the use of differential aileron movement.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The Frise-type aileron also forms a slot, so air flows smoothly over the lowered aileron, making it more effective at high angles of attack.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Frise-type ailerons may also be designed to function differentially.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Like the differential aileron, the Frise-type aileron does not eliminate adverse yaw entirely.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Coordinated rudder application is still needed when ailerons are applied.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] By careful design of the mechanical linkages, the up aileron can be made to deflect more than the down aileron (e.g., US patent 1,565,097).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] This helps reduce the likelihood of a wing tip stall when aileron deflections are made at high angles of attack.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] In addition, the consequent differential in drag reduces adverse yaw (as also discussed above).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The idea is that the loss of lift associated with the up aileron carries no penalty while the increase in lift associated with the down aileron is minimized.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The rolling couple on the aircraft is always the difference in lift between the two wings.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] A designer at de Havilland invented a simple and practical linkage and their de Havilland Tiger Moth classic British biplane became one of the best-known aircraft, and one of the earliest, to use differential ailerons.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] On the earliest Pioneer Era aircraft, such as the Wright Flyer and the later, 1909-origin Blériot XI and Etrich Taube, lateral control was effected by twisting the outboard portion of the wing so as to increase or decrease lift by changing the angle of attack.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] This had the disadvantages of stressing the structure, being heavy on the controls, and of risking stalling the side with the increased angle of attack during a maneuver.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] By 1916, most designers had abandoned wing warping in favor of ailerons.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Researchers at NASA and elsewhere have been taking a second look at wing warping again, although under new names.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The NASA version is the X-53 Active Aeroelastic Wing while the United States Air Force tested the Adaptive Compliant Wing.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Spoilers are devices that when extended into the airflow over a wing, disrupt the airflow and reduce the amount of lift generated.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Many modern aircraft designs, especially jet aircraft, use spoilers in lieu of, or to supplement ailerons, such as the F4 Phantom II and Northrop P-61 Black Widow, which had almost full width flaps (there were very small conventional ailerons at the wingtips as well).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] All aircraft with dihedral have some form of yaw-roll coupling to promote stability.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Common trainers like the Cessna 152/172 series can be roll controlled with rudder alone.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] The rudder of the Boeing 737 has more roll authority over the aircraft than the ailerons at high angles of attack.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] This led to two notable accidents when the rudder jammed in the fully deflected position causing rollovers (see Boeing 737 rudder issues).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Some aircraft such as the Fokker Spin and model gliders lack any type of lateral control.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Those aircraft use a higher amount of dihedral than conventional aircraft.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/aileron] Deflecting the rudder gives yaw and a lot of differential wing lift, giving a yaw induced roll moment.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] Bovik received a Primetime Emmy Award in 2015 for his development of perception-based video quality measurement tools that are now standards in television production.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] Al Bovik was educated at the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign (PhD 1984).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] He has made numerous fundamental contributions to the fields of digital photography, digital television, digital image processing, digital video processing, digital cinema, and computational visual perception.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] He is particularly well known for his work on low-level vision, natural scene modeling, image quality, and video quality.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] He has published more than 1000 technical articles, books, and patents in these areas.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] Overall, his work has been cited in the scientific and engineering literature more than 200,000 times according to Google Scholar.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] He is one of the most highly cited engineers in the world according to the Web of Science.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] Bovik is an elected member of the United States National Academy of Engineering (NAE), an elected Foreign Fellow of the Indian National Academy of Engineering (INAE), an elected Fellow of the U.S.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] National Academy of Inventors, and an elected foreign member of Academia Europaea (2023).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] He is also a Life Fellow of the IEEE, a Fellow of Optica and of the Society of Photo-Optical and Instrumentation Engineers (SPIE), an Honorary Fellow of the Royal Photographic Society (HonFRPS) and an Honorary Member of the Society for Imaging Science and Technology (IS&T).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] He is a voting member of the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences (Television Academy) and was named an inaugural member of its Science and Technology Peer Group.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] He was named a Distinguished Alumnus of the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign in 2008.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] His high-dynamic range (HDR) add-on model HDRMAX, which improves the quality prediction performance of leading models is marketed and used worldwide.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] He was the founder and First General Chair of the IEEE International Conference on Image Processing (ICIP).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] He also co-founded (with David Munson, Jr.) the IEEE Transactions on Image Processing and was its longest-serving Editor-in-Chief, with a tenure of six years.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] Bovik's academic legacy includes serving as the supervising professor of more than 70 PhD graduates, more than 50 master's degree recipients, and more than two dozen post-doctoral researchers.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] His award-winning online courseware is used internationally: SIVA – Courseware for Signal, Image, Video and Audio Processing.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] This online courseware offers online curricula for digital image and video processing and digital signal processing.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] SIVA includes hundreds of signal, image and video processing demonstrations delivering live, interactive audio-visual experiences of signal and image processing algorithms.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alan-bovik] Bovik has received a number of major international awards.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Sperry's compasses and stabilizers were adopted by the United States Navy and used in both world wars.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] He also worked closely with Japanese companies and the Japanese government and was honored after his death with a volume of reminiscences published in Japan.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Sperry was born in Cincinnatus, New York, on October 12, 1860, to Stephen Decatur Sperry and Mary Burst.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] His mother died the next day, from complications from his birth.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] His family had been in what is now the Northeastern United States since the 1600s, and his earliest American ancestor was an English colonist named Richard Sperry (born 1606).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Sperry spent three years at the State Normal School in Cortland, New York, then a year at Cornell University in 1878 and 1879, where he became interested in dynamos.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] He moved to Chicago, Illinois, early in 1880 and soon after founded the Sperry Electric Company.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] He married Zula Augusta Goodman (1860-1929) in Chicago, Illinois on June 28, 1887.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1887, Sperry created a system to bring electricity into coal mines, heating the copper wires to prevent corrosion.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] This system allowed him to bring self-designed mining equipment deep below the surface, to greatly increase the production of coal.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1888 the Sperry Electric Machinery Mining Company was founded.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1890, Sperry formed the Sperry Electric Railway Company.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Here he used ideas from the electric trains sold by his mining company to create electric trolleys in large, hilly cities in Ohio and Pennsylvania.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] While working with this company, Sperry designed an electric automobile, which led to Sperry patenting ideas that would be later used in the development of portable lead acid batteries.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1896, he drove his car in Paris, making it the first American-made car in Paris.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1894, General Electric bought the railway company and its associated patents.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1900 Sperry established an electrochemical laboratory at Washington, D.C., where he and his associate, Clifton P.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Townshend, developed a process for making pure caustic soda and discovered a process for recovering tin from scrap metal.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] After experiencing seasickness on an Atlantic voyage in 1898, Sperry started to work on incorporating a large gyroscope into a ship to lessen the effect of waves on the ship.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] His gyroscope-stabilized ship differed from others at the time by having a sensor built in to the system to detect the first signs of a wave that the system would have to work to mitigate.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1911, Sperry worked with the US Navy to incorporate his gyroscopic stabilizer, which greatly reduced major roll of the ship, into Navy ships.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] While effective, Sperry's gyrostabilizer never was widely sold because of its expense, both in installation and maintenance.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Sperry found another use for his gyroscopes in 1908.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Magnetic compasses on steel battleships at the time had issues with maintaining magnetic north with the variations of the magnetic field they experienced.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Ford, Sperry began work on a gyrocompass to replace the magnetic compass.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1910 he founded the Sperry Gyroscope Company in Brooklyn, New York on the basis of this innovation.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] His first navigational gyroscope was tested that same year in USS *Delaware* (BB-28).
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] After successful tests, Sperry's gyrocompass was soon being installed on American, British, French, Italian, and Russian naval crafts.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] During World War I, the importance of the gyrocompass increased as the compass was adapted to control the steering of a ship to automatically hold a steady line.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1913, working with his son Lawrence Burst Sperry, Sperry created a gyro that could control the elevators and ailerons of an aircraft through a series of servomechanisms.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Sperry successfully implemented his gyrostabilizer technology, formerly thought to be only applicable to large ships, because of their high weight, into aircraft.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In June 1914, Sperry and his son won the Aero Club of France's competition to build a safer aircraft, demonstrating the stabilizer with his son doing a "no-hands" flight past the judges.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] He also was awarded a Franklin Institute Medal in the same year.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] This gyrostabilization system, while never implemented on a massive scale, laid the foundation for his son's autopilot system.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1916, Sperry joined Peter Hewitt to develop the Hewitt-Sperry Automatic Airplane, one of the first successful precursors of the UAV.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1917, Sperry solved the issue of magnetic compasses indicating the opposite position when an aircraft is turning, inventing the Gyro Turn Indicator.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] This turn indicator was later modified into what is known now as the Turn and Slip Indicator.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] With a Directional Gyro and Gyro Horizon added later, Sperry created a core of flight instruments that became standard equipment on all aircraft.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] During both world wars, Sperry's company profited from military demand for gyroscopes.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] His technology was subsequently used in torpedoes, ships, airplanes, and spacecraft.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Sperry moved into related devices such as bombsights, fire control, radar, and automated take off and landing.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] During World War I he worked to create a "flying bomb", and on March 6, 1918, he guided an aerial torpedo for more than half a mile using radio control.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Working with the US Navy, Sperry developed a system to control the entire battery of a battleship from an interior room of the ship.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] This control system used his gyroscopic equipment to correct an individual gun's position based on changes in course of the ship, allowing the entire battery to remain focused on one point.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] This control system was installed on all battleships of the United States Navy during World War I.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Sperry was a founding member of the U.S.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Starting in 1914, Sperry began working with the US Navy to develop higher-power lighting for use with naval turrets.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] Out of this partnership, Sperry and his team created a new kind of arc lamp that heated a gas to incandescence, creating a source of light five times brighter than other continuous light sources of the time.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1918 he produced a high-intensity arc lamp which was used as a searchlight by both the Army and Navy.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In 1923, Sperry's son Lawrence died in the English Channel in the crash of an airplane of his own design.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] In January 1929, Sperry sold his Sperry Gyroscope Company to North American Aviation.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] The following year his wife died, on March 31, in Havana, Cuba.
[src:elmer-ambrose-sperry/elmer-ambrose-sperry] John Hospital in Brooklyn, New York, on June 16, 1930, from complications following the removal of gallstones six weeks earlier.
